State MSM Profile: Wisconsin

Background & Methods

In 2015-2016, researchers at Emory University partnered with colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to develop methods to estimate the number of men who have sex with men (MSM) residing in each county in the United States. Using population and housing data from the American Community Survey and estimates from two peer-reviewed publications (Oster et al., 2015 & Purcell et al., 2012), they derived an indirect estimate of MSM population sizes that took into account both the urbanicity of the county as well as its density of households with a male householder and a male same-sex partner.

The full methodology is published in the Journal of Medical Internet Research - Public Health and Surveillance:

Grey JA, Bernstein KT, Sullivan PS, Purcell DW, Chesson HW, Gift TL, Rosenberg ES. Estimating the population sizes of men who have sex with men in US states and counties using data from the American Community Survey. JMIR Public Health Surveill 2016;2(1):e14. DOI: 10.2196/publichealth.5365

Overview of MSM in Wisconsin

An estimated 59,077 men who have sex with men (MSM) resided in Wisconsin in 2013, representing 1.3% of the 4,503,084 MSM in the United States. Of the 2,154,753 adult men of Wisconsin, 2.7% had had sex with another man in the past 5 years, which was less than the overall percentage of adult men in the United States who were MSM (3.9%).

Most MSM in Wisconsin resided in counties within medium or small metropolitan areas (34.0%). Including both central and fringe counties, 50.1% resided in a large metropolitan area.


Percentage of MSM by urbanicity, United States and Wisconsin, 2013

MSM in Wisconsin Counties

Among counties or county-equivalent areas in Wisconsin, Milwaukee County had the largest population of MSM at 18,427, representing 31.2% of all MSM in the state. Door County had the highest percentage of MSM among adult men in Wisconsin at 5.9%. This was greater than the percentage for Wisconsin as a whole, which was 2.7% of adult men.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.



MSM in Wisconsin Metropolitan Statistical Areas

Milwaukee-Waukesha-West Allis Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Milwaukee-Waukesha-West Allis MSA had the largest metropolitan population of MSM in Wisconsin at 26,352, or 44.6% of all MSM in the state. Of the 566,172 adult men in Milwaukee-Waukesha-West Allis, an estimated 4.7% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Madison Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Madison MSA had a population of 6,597 MSM, or 11.2% of all MSM in Wisconsin. Of the 236,154 adult men in Madison, an estimated 2.8% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Green Bay Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Green Bay MSA had a population of 2,411 MSM, or 4.1% of all MSM in Wisconsin. Of the 115,441 adult men in Green Bay, an estimated 2.1% were MSM.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




Chicago-Naperville-Elgin Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Chicago-Naperville-Elgin MSA overlaps three states: Illinois, Indiana and Wisconsin. The Wisconsin portion of the MSA had 1,904 MSM, or 3.2% of all MSM in the state and 1.1% of the 175,118 MSM in the MSA. Of 60,995 adult men in the Wisconsin part of Chicago-Naperville-Elgin, 3.1% were MSM. This was less than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 5.1% of adult men (175,118 out of 3,443,489).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.
